
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `id` baraye namayesh etela'at karbari mesle `UID`, `GID`, va group-hayei ke karbar ozv ast, estefade mishavad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `id`     --> 👤 Namayesh `UID`, `GID`, va group-haye karbar current.
    🔹 `id -u`  --> 🔢 Namayesh faghat `UID` karbar.
    🔹 `id -g`  --> 🔢 Namayesh faghat `GID` karbar.
    🔹 `id -n`  --> 📝 Namayesh name be jaye shomare (`UID`/`GID`).
    🔹 `id -G`  --> 👥 Namayesh hameye ID-haye group karbar.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ id

    🔹 Namayesh etela'at karbar mesle `uid`, `gid`, va group-ha.

    $ id -u
    
    🔹 Namayesh faghat `UID` karbar.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ id -nG

    🔹 Namayesh name group-ha be jaye ID-haye adadi. In baraye ghabl khan kardan khroji komak mikonad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `id` command is used to display user identity information such as `UID`, `GID`, and group memberships.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `id`     --> 👤 Display `UID`, `GID`, and groups for the current user.
    🔹 `id -u`  --> 🔢 Display only the user ID (`UID`).
    🔹 `id -g`  --> 🔢 Display only the group ID (`GID`).
    🔹 `id -n`  --> 📝 Display names instead of numbers (`UID`/`GID`).
    🔹 `id -G`  --> 👥 Display all group IDs the user is a member of.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ id

    🔹 Display user identity information including `uid`, `gid`, and groups.

    $ id -u

    🔹 Display only the user ID (`UID`).

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ id -nG

    🔹 Display group names instead of numerical IDs.  This helps make the output more readable.
